{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:28:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15975"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15975"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.05,0.25,0.25,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15975"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58320"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20751"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe human embryo develops several extraembryonic membranes during early development. These structures provide essential support for normal embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the human yolk sac?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms the primitive gut tube","Provides mechanical protection","Produces blood cells and germ cells","Stores maternal nutrients","Secretes human chorionic gonadotropin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduction of blood cells and germ cells\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the human yolk sac. It is the first site of blood cell formation (haematopoiesis) and gives rise to primordial germ cells that later migrate to form the gonads.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms the primitive gut tube\u003C/strong\u003E - While the yolk sac contributes to gut development via the vitelline duct, this is not its primary function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvides mechanical protection\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the function of the amniotic sac\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStores maternal nutrients\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike in birds, the human yolk sac does not serve as a nutrient storage organ\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretes human chorionic gonadotropin\u003C/strong\u003E - This hormone is produced by the developing placenta, not the yolk sac\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe yolk sac forms during the second week of development from extraembryonic endoderm and mesoderm. While it becomes relatively smaller as pregnancy progresses, it remains present and connected to the midgut through the vitelline duct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The yolk sac forms from extraembryonic endoderm and mesoderm during the second week of development","The yolk sac produces the first blood cells and primordial germ cells in human embryos","The yolk sac remains connected to the midgut through the vitelline duct during development"],"references":["Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58320"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15975"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58320"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T10:01:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T10:02:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8666"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72850"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonym